 {"id": ["NCBIGene:3091"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HIF1&alpha;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9978558421134949, "span": {"begin": 1023, "end": 1034}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:405"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ARNT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9918146729469299, "span": {"begin": 1039, "end": 1043}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3091"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HIF1&alpha;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9981184005737305, "span": {"begin": 1076, "end": 1087}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:405"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ARNT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9857742786407471, "span": {"begin": 1088, "end": 1092}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AHR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.968946635723114, "span": {"begin": 1118, "end": 1121}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8942923545837402, "span": {"begin": 1127, "end": 1131}}], "text": "Include consideration of temporal concordance here     Activation of either AHR (by 2,3,7,8-tetrachlorodibenzo-p-dioxin) or HIF1 (by hypoxia) inhibits the activity of the other, in Hep3B cells (Chan et al. 1999)  TCDD and hypoxia together reduced the stabilization of HIF1&alpha; and HRE-mediated promoter activity when compared to hypoxia alone, in MCF-7 and HepG2 cells (Seifert et al. 2008).  Hypoxia increased EF5 binding (hypoxic tissue marker) in chicken embryos, whereas it was decreased by TCDD relative to controls (D10 of incubation) (Ivnitski-Steele et al. 2004)  TCDD reduces the expression of cardiac HIF1&alpha; mRNA in chicken embryos (Ivnitski-Steele et al. 2004)  ARNT overexpression rescued human HepG2 and HaCaT cells from inhibitory effect of hypoxia on XRE-luciferase reporter activity. This indicates that the mechanism of interference between the AHR and HIF1&alpha; pathways at least partially dependent on ARNT availability (Vorrink et al. 2014)  Ischemia-induced upregulation of the expression of HIF1&alpha; and ARNT and DNA binding activity of the HIF1&alpha;-ARNT complex were enhanced in AHR-null mice (Ichihara et al. 2007).  Vorrink et al (2014b) provides a thorough summary of supporting evidence as well as contradictions and uncertainties in the literature.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:53:44 +0000 2026"}